2026-04-21 01:39:53 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module internal controller / oscillator circuit (between light sensor, potentiometers, and relay coil)'] hypothesis_explanation='The lamp supply is periodically interrupted (~0.5 s every 20 s). Power from the supply module is stable (indicator LED solid), and the load module behaves correctly because the lamp always comes back on with normal brightness and a correct polarity‑blocking diode arrangement. The relay contacts in the ambient sensor module are observed mechanically closed and healthy, and sweeping both the timing and sensitivity potentiometers through their entire ranges has no effect at all on the flicker interval or duty cycle.\n\nIn a correctly working system, that 20‑second on/off timing must be generated by the ambient sensor module’s control electronics (an oscillator / threshold circuit that drives the relay coil) and must be influenced by at least one of the two potentiometers and by the light sensor. The fact that the period and duty remain unchanged when both potentiometers are fully adjusted strongly indicates that the timing/sensitivity network is no longer effectively connected to the control circuit, or that the control IC itself has failed into a quasi‑stable oscillatory state that ignores its inputs while still intermittently dropping the drive to the relay coil.\n\nThus the most likely single fault is within the ambient sensor module’s internal controller/oscillator circuitry (between the light sensor + potentiometers and the relay coil), not the battery, wiring, relay contacts, or load module. Replacing/repairing that control circuit should eliminate the regular 20‑second flicker.'
