is connected to Control Input Cable (−), and PSU Output Cable (−) is connected to Control Input Cable (+). 
Of course, the presence of a small negative current in one cable, by itself, does not amount to polarity inversion. "


ACTION:
With the system powered and the lamp exhibiting its ~20 s flicker, monitor the voltage at the control module’s output terminals (the pair going to the load) relative to the power‑supply negative using a fast DMM or oscilloscope. Observe whether the output ever drops or glitches when the lamp goes off for 0.5 s. In parallel, probe directly across the relay’s switched contacts (input vs output) to see if there is any transient opening or significant resistance change synchronized with the flicker, even though the relay appears mechanically closed.
