2026-04-21 01:42:33 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['light‑sensor element in ambient sensor module (photo‑device itself)'] hypothesis_explanation='All voltage, continuity, relay‑contact, cabling, and load‑module tests show a completely stable 11.8–12 V supply right through to the lamp terminals, with both the main and indicator lamps holding ~11 V across them and never actually turning fully off during the alleged 0.5 s ‘outage’. The relay is confirmed continuously closed and its driver and timing/oscillation network have been replaced/tested with no effect. The simulator, however, repeatedly reports that the *circuit* is in an unstable or oscillating state, even while all power rails remain steady and all other components behave normally.\n\nThe only remaining element capable of producing a slow (~20 s) internal oscillation without disturbing the measured DC path to the lamp is the light‑sensor device itself in the ambient sensor module. A partially faulty photo‑device (e.g., photodiode/phototransistor with abnormal leakage or capacitance) can create a high‑gain feedback loop in combination with the controller’s high input impedance, causing local oscillation or metastable behavior of the internal controller node. This can place the *simulation* into a numerically unstable state (reported oscillation) while the relay output is held solidly in the ON state, so the lamp voltage appears constant. All other candidate elements in that loop (controller, timing network, indicator branch, relay contacts, cabling, lamps, and battery) have been specifically ruled out by repair attempts and measurements.\n\nTherefore the most plausible remaining root cause is a defective light‑sensor element in the ambient sensor module; replacing that photo‑device should eliminate the internal oscillation that the simulator flags and restore a stable operating point for the overall system.'
