2026-04-21 01:42:54 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module internal power / reference‑supply decoupling network (e.g., supply bypass capacitor or reference‑stabilizing capacitor that is either missing, mis‑valued, or mis‑connected, causing a slow 20‑s relaxation oscillation while all main I/O voltages look DC‑steady)'] hypothesis_explanation='All measured DC node voltages from the battery through the control‑module output to the load and across both lamps remain essentially constant (~11–12 V) during the reported 20‑s / 0.5‑s flicker, and both lamps are observed lit whenever directly checked. The relay contacts stay closed with no discernible resistance change, the lamps, diode, battery, LEDs, cabling, light sensor, and the controller’s primary timing network have all effectively been ruled out by prior targeted repair attempts. Yet the simulator repeatedly reports that the circuit is in an unstable or oscillating state, and this oscillation cannot be attributed to any of the already‑tested timing or functional components.\n\nThe only remaining plausible root cause consistent with: (1) persistent, low‑frequency oscillation detected by the simulator; (2) no observable change in the main power rails or relay state at human‑scale measurements; and (3) the absence of faults in the obvious timing and control elements, is a problem in the internal supply/reference decoupling of the ambient sensor module’s controller. A missing or incorrect value/wiring of the controller’s local bypass or reference capacitor can produce a very slow relaxation or hunting behavior in the internal bias/reference voltage without significantly modulating the 11.8 V module rails or the relay drive beyond the resolution of our measurements. This would be seen by the simulator as an unstable operating point or slow oscillation, even while the externally measured DC voltages look steady and all discrete components pass simple tests.\n\nTherefore, I hypothesize that the internal power/reference‑supply decoupling network of the ambient sensor module’s controller (e.g., its bypass capacitor or associated wiring) is faulty (missing, wrong, or mis‑connected), leading to the observed simulation‑reported oscillation and the user‑perceived 20‑second flicker behavior.'
