2026-04-21 01:43:03 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['wiring / polarity of the power‑supply module’s two external cables (PSU output leads swapped at the battery terminals inside the PSU box)'] hypothesis_explanation='All three modules and their internal components have repeatedly tested good, with stable 11.8–12 V seen from the PSU right through to the lamps, and both lamps continuously see about 11 V with no actual interruption captured at their terminals. Yet the simulator keeps reporting an unstable/oscillating state corresponding to a perceived 20‑s / 0.5‑s flicker that cannot be substantiated by electrical measurements.\n\nThe only remaining plausible fault consistent with: (1) correct polarity between the control and load modules, (2) intact series diode in the load, (3) normal operation of the ambient‑sensor relay and its indicators, and (4) correct overall DC levels, is a subtle mis‑wiring of the *power‑supply module’s own output leads* relative to the battery inside the PSU box. If the PSU’s external “+” and “−” leads are internally swapped at the battery (or at the LED/resistor reference node), the system could be operating with reversed reference for some sub‑circuits so that the simulator’s notion of ground and the physical circuit’s ground are inconsistent. This would allow all measured differential voltages (between the labeled + and − rails) to appear correct and stable, and the lamps to remain visibly on, while the analysis engine detects an apparent long‑period oscillation due to the mis‑referenced node and internal indicator/feedback paths.\n\nThus the root cause is not a failed component but a wiring/polarity fault at the PSU module’s internal output connection to the battery terminals. Correcting the PSU output‑lead polarity at the battery should eliminate the spurious oscillatory behavior and reconcile the simulator’s state with the observed, continuously lit lamp.'
