2026-04-21 01:43:15 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['wiring of the small internal indicator lamp in the load module (misconnected so it is NOT actually in parallel with the main lamp but instead in a different node/path)'] hypothesis_explanation='All voltage and continuity measurements show a stable 11.8–12 V from the battery through the PSU and control module right up to the load‑module input and across the main lamp terminals, with no 0.5 s drop or interruption when the user‑reported “flicker” occurs. Both the external lamp and the internal indicator lamp remain lit and at full supply voltage during the supposed off intervals. The simulator, however, reports a non‑convergent / oscillatory state while the human observation test confirms the main lamp is simply lit.\n\nThe only remaining way to reconcile: (1) constant DC voltages and currents everywhere in the documented series path; (2) both lamps energized continuously; and (3) a simulator that nonetheless finds an internal oscillation, is that the model’s *topology* differs from the intended schematic. A topology‑level error is not a faulty component per se but a wrong interconnection. The most plausible location is the extra internal indicator lamp branch in the load module, which is the only additional element able to create alternative current paths or feedback without showing up at the module input terminals.\n\nIf that internal indicator lamp (or its node connections) is miswired so it is not actually in simple parallel with the main lamp—as described in the design—but instead tied to an unintended node (for example, referenced to some internal sensor or return path rather than directly between the load + and − rails), the physical lamps can still appear steadily lit at near‑nominal voltage while the simulator’s internal node equations include a spurious feedback loop that never reaches a stable operating point and manifests as an artificial 20‑s oscillation. All earlier tests focusing on component health (diode, lamps, relay, controller, sensor, battery, cables) would naturally pass, since the parts themselves are fine; only the wiring of the indicator branch is wrong.\n\nTherefore the root cause is a wiring / interconnection error of the small indicator lamp inside the load module, which is not actually in the intended parallel configuration with the main lamp and is instead forming an unintended network that drives the observed simulation instability and the user’s initial misinterpretation of a periodic lamp outage.'
